{
  "texts": [
    "Some, like Hewitt et al. [59] and Aher et al.",
    "[61], focus on lab-based designs; others, such as Chen et al. [63], move into applied, field-based contexts.",
    "Together, these studies reveal the flexibility of LLMs as tools for experimental replication, while also underscoring the methodological boundaries that remain-particularly in modeling cultural nuance, intersectionality, and higher-order interactions.",
    "These findings support a promising but qualified conclusion: LLMs are capable of modeling many human decision-making patterns and treatment effects, but their reliability varies across domains, demographic contexts, and task complexity.",
    "While replications in controlled settings often capture main effects, challenges remain in modeling interaction effects [62], culturally grounded reasoning [63], and individual variability [61].Rather than serving as a replacement for human experimentation, LLM-based simulation should be understood as a complementary approach to theory testing."
  ]
}